article.description: Nykesha Sales scored 19 points to lead the Sun to a 73-57 win over the Comets on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Sales helps East-leading Sun to easy win over Comets
article.linkText: Sales helps East-leading Sun to easy win over Comets
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- With Nykesha Sales and Katie Douglas powering the offense and 7-foot-2 center Margo Dydek creating havoc on defense, the Connecticut Sun can be one of the toughest teams in the WNBA to beat.

The Houston Comets found that out the hard way Tuesday night.

Sales scored a game-high 19 points to lead the Sun to a 73-57 win over the Comets.

The Eastern Conference-leading Sun (11-4) opened the game with a 12-2 run and held the Comets to eight points in the opening quarter.

"You can't drop behind a quality basketball team like that on the road and beat anybody, it's just pure and simple," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "We just couldn't make a shot."

The Sun opened a 25-point lead on a layup by Sales 2:16 into the third quarter.

"We knew that we had to get off to a good start to play a good game against Houston," Dydek said. "That's what we did. We didn't let people like Sheryl Swoopes or Tina Thompson score a lot of points. [But] at the end, when we had a big lead, it was kind of difficult to stay focused."

That helped the Comets (10-6) make a game of it in the fourth quarter. Houston put together a 15-5 run that cut the deficit to 11 points with 1:39 left, but the Sun held on thanks to a pair of free throws by Lindsay Whalen and a 3-pointer by Katie Douglas.

Douglas finished with 15 points. Dydek had 10 points and 13 rebounds for her third double-double of the season, as well as three blocked shots. Whalen also had 10 points to go with six assists and three steals.

"I have watched us give away leads, but I had a sense that our starters had figured out defensively how to play," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "We needed a playoff-atmosphere win. That's what we were going for tonight."

Dawn Staley scored 14 of her season-high 17 points in the second half for the Comets. Michelle Snow had 14 points and 12 rebounds. Sheryl Swoopes was held to nine points on 4-of-15 shooting, while Tina Thompson was held to a season-low two points on 1-of-12 shooting.

The Comets made only 24-of-71 shots (33.8 percent) and turned the ball over 20 times.

"Connecticut did a great job tonight. They really, really moved the ball well and Douglas and Sales just shot the eyes out of it," Chancellor said. "Margo plays [well] against the Comets when she doesn't play [well] against another team. When she plays against us, she has just been a Comets killer. Once again, she clogged up the middle."
